PARAGRAPH.#text: NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--Only one issuer opted to come to the U.S. bond market with new debt on Tuesday, despite a fairly positive tone to the market early morning. PPL Energy Supply LLC PPL sold $500 million of 10-year, 4.60% coupon notes at a yield of 4.604%, for a spread of 262.5 basis points over Treasurys. When the deal was first marketed, it was for $350 million. The issue could plausibly be the final investment-grade marketing of 2011. Syndicate desks said issuers tapping the market this late in the year are opportunistic borrowers rather than ones in dire need of funding, and with the secondary market weakening in the afternoon after the Federal Reserve said global market strains "continue to pose significant downside risks to the economic outlook," few issuers will feel invited to try their luck later in the week.

Headlines.Headline: Mercury Emissions Up Among 50 US Coal-Fired Pwr Plants-Study

PARAGRAPH.#text: SAN FRANCISCO (Dow Jones)--Mercury emissions are on the rise from older U.S. coal-fired power plants, according to a study released Thursday. Fifty coal-fired power plants in Texas, Pennsylvania, Alabama, Georgia and eight other states produced more emissions of mercury in 2007 than they did the previous year, according to the study, by the Washington-based Environmental Integrity Project. Together, the plants emitted 20 tons of mercury in 2007. While most of the plants produced more mercury emissions in 2007 year over year, some of them produced fewer of those emissions, said the not-for-profit group, which advocates for stiffer enforcement of environmental laws.

Headlines.Author: Mary Kennedy
Headlines.Headline: Gold shines amid weak greenback

#text:
NEW YORK (CBS.MW) -- Let it shine, let
    it shine, let it shine! February
    gold

soared to a two-month high Friday, rising 3.1 percent as the U.S. dollar slid
    against most major foreign currencies and warehoused supplies declined. The U.S. dollar
    hit a two-month low against the Japanese yen and a three-week low against the German mark.
    The price of gold, denominated in U.S. dollars, fluctuates with the value of the dollar.
    Additionally, gold stocks in exchange-certified warehouses declined 8,653 ounces to
    442,237 ounces.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Gold shines amid weak greenback

    information is based; converted funds, in which a new mutual fund is created from an
    existing investment; and composite performance, allowing the use of performance
